{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"e0578df7-07ca-46b7-b33a-d34e40592f5e","content":"## The Problem\n\n**.NET MAUI Android builds ignore `JAVA_HOME`**. The build system uses its own `JavaSdkDirectory` MSBuild property, which defaults to the Microsoft OpenJDK installed by the workload — not your system JDK.\n\nYour Temurin installation is fine, but MSBuild isn't looking at it.\n\n## Fixes (pick one)\n\n**Option A** — Install the workload's bundled JDK (recommended):\n```bash\ndotnet workload install maui-android\n```\nThis installs Microsoft's OpenJDK 17 to the path MSBuild expects.\n\n**Option B** — Point MSBuild at your Temurin JDK by adding this to your `.csproj`:\n```xml\n<PropertyGroup>\n  <JavaSdkDirectory>/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home</JavaSdkDirectory>\n</PropertyGroup>\n```\n\n**Option C** — Pass it on the command line:\n```bash\ndotnet build -p:JavaSdkDirectory=/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home\n```\n\nOption A is simplest since it keeps everything managed by the dotnet workload tooling.","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"fd064db7-f72d-4c31-8391-808f55a3dc69","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is having a .NET MAUI Android build failure with a Java-related error on macOS. They have Adoptium Temurin JDK 17.0.12 installed with JAVA_HOME pointing to it.\n\nLet me think about what common issues exist with .NET MAUI Android builds and Java on macOS:\n\nThe key issue here is likely related to the JAVA_HOME path on macOS. On macOS, the Adoptium Temurin JDK installs to a path like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`, but .NET MAUI / Android SDK tools expect JAVA_HOME to point to specific locations.\n \nI'm realizing that .NET 8+ ships with its own Microsoft OpenJDK distribution, and the Android build tools might have specific requirements about which JDK version is used. The issue could stem from a few places: .NET MAUI might expect the Microsoft OpenJDK specifically rather than Adoptium Temurin, the macOS path might need to include `Contents/Home`, or there could be a version compatibility mismatch between the JDK and the Android build tools.\n\nThe most likely culprit on macOS is that the JAVA_HOME path for Temurin needs to be set correctly—something like `/Library/Java/JavaVirtualMachines/temurin-17.jdk/Contents/Home`—and if it's pointing to the wrong location, the build will fail even though the JDK version itself is compatible. The workload installer places Microsoft's OpenJDK at a specific location, and if JAVA_HOME points elsewhere, the build might pick up an incompatible version. On Apple Silicon Macs especially, there's often an architecture mismatch—either an x86_64 JDK running on ARM64 hardware or vice versa—which would definitely cause Java-related build failures with Temurin 17.0.12.\n\nBut I think the real culprit is that .NET MAUI Android doesn't actually use JAVA_HOME by default—it relies on its own bundled Microsoft OpenJDK configured during installation. If that workload didn't install properly or was skipped, the build fails with a Java error even though JAVA_HOME is set. The solution would be reinstalling the Microsoft OpenJDK through the workload installer, or manually pointing to the correct JDK location.\n\nActually, there's a specific macOS issue I'm remembering: .NET 8/9 MAUI ignores JAVA_HOME entirely and looks for the JDK at a hardcoded path like `~/Library/Developer/Xamarin/jdk/` instead. If the JDK isn't at that expected location, you get a cryptic error.\n\nThe solution is either reinstalling the Android workload to set everything up correctly, or manually pointing the `<JavaSdkDirectory>` property in the project file to the Temurin installation path.\n\nActually, I should clarify the real issue here. The .NET Android build system doesn't use JAVA_HOME at all—it looks for the JDK installed by the workload itself, typically in the Developer directory. Even though the user has Temurin set up with JAVA_HOME configured, the build fails because MSBuild can't find the JDK at the location it expects, which is where the workload installs it.\n\nThe solution is straightforward: either install the workload which brings the Microsoft OpenJDK, or manually point the project to the Temurin installation by adding a JavaSdkDirectory property to the project file.","outputTokens":2139,"requestId":"0819:3D4AC3:A23A6C:BBC5F7:69F2A7E8"},"id":"e4f7c6b1-ab21-47b0-af79-1a4356ce817f","timestamp":"2026-04-30T00:53:35.568Z","parentId":"67d9f212-9049-4883-8b86-61745c04390e"}
